README.md
     1‚Üílog
     3‚Üí
     4‚ÜíA Rust library providing a lightweight logging *facade*.
     5‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    19‚Üí## Minimum supported `rustc`
    20‚Üí
    21‚Üí`1.68.0+`
    22‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
    25‚Üí## Usage
    26‚Üí
    27‚Üí### In libraries
    28‚Üí
    29‚ÜíLibraries should link only to the `log` crate, and use the provided macros to
    30‚Üílog whatever information will be useful to downstream consumers:
    31‚Üí
    32‚Üí```toml
    33‚Üí[dependencies]
    34‚Üílog = "0.4"
    35‚Üí```
    36‚Üí
    37‚Üí```rust
    38‚Üíuse log::{info, trace, warn};
    39‚Üí
    40‚Üípub fn shave_the_yak(yak: &mut Yak) {
    41‚Üí    trace!("Commencing yak shaving");
    42‚Üí
    43‚Üí    loop {
    44‚Üí        match find_a_razor() {
    45‚Üí            Ok(razor) => {
    46‚Üí                info!("Razor located: {razor}");
    47‚Üí                yak.shave(razor);
    48‚Üí                break;
    49‚Üí            }
    50‚Üí            Err(err) => {
    51‚Üí                warn!("Unable to locate a razor: {err}, retrying");
    52‚Üí            }
    53‚Üí        }
    54‚Üí    }
    55‚Üí}
    56‚Üí```
    57‚Üí
    58‚Üí### In executables
    59‚Üí
    60‚ÜíIn order to produce log output, executables have to use a logger implementation compatible with the facade.
    61‚ÜíThere are many available implementations to choose from, here are some options:
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
   106‚Üí## Structured logging
   107‚Üí
   108‚ÜíIf you enable the `kv` feature, you can associate structured data with your log records:
   109‚Üí
      ‚Üí‚Ä¶
rfcs/0296-structured-logging.md
   502‚Üí### Don't break anything
   503‚Üí
   504‚ÜíAllow structured logging to be added in the current `0.4.x` series of `log`. This gives us the option of including structured logging in an `0.4.x` release, or bumping the minor crate version without introducing any actual breaking changes.
   505‚Üí
  1598‚Üí#### Build a serialization contract in `log`
  1599‚Üí
  1600‚ÜíInstead of internalizing a few serialization frameworks, `log` could provide a public common contract for them to conform to:
  1601‚Üí
  1602‚Üí```rust
  1603‚Üí// Instead of `Value::from_any` + `FromAny`
  1604‚Üí
  1605‚Üípub trait Visit {
  1606‚Üí    fn visit(&self, visitor: &mut dyn Visitor) -> Result<(), Error>;
  1607‚Üí}
  1608‚Üí
  1609‚Üípub trait Visitor {
  1610‚Üí    fn u64(&mut self, v: u64) -> Result<(), Error>;
  1611‚Üí    fn i64(&mut self, v: i64) -> Result<(), Error>;
  1612‚Üí
  1613‚Üí    ..
  1614‚Üí}
  1615‚Üí```
  1616‚Üí
